@NODE "Mail_2" " Re: Amiga/ Blitz MUGEN "
From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: 11-30-00 14:06:02
Subject: @{b}Re: Amiga/ Blitz MUGEN@{ub}

Hello Jason Faramus,

> charaters and backgrounds/ moves etc... and put them all together in a very
> professional looking game (Capcom style). Am I wrong in believing that the Amiga
> could pull a similar thing off seeing as it specializes in 2-D graphics, unlike
> PC's?

Before I start, I think it's possible, but it might be tricky.

If you are going to make it a blitz mode game (i.e. hardware banging), apart 
from annoying everyone with a graphics card (and sound card, and not being able 
to use pretty much any other piece of hardware during the fight sequences), you 
are going to be limited to using chipram, which isn't the fastest in the world. 
And if you need a 256 colour screenmode...

You won't be able to use dual playfields (unless you can somehow make the 
graphics work in 32 colours). This leaves you with the choice of using sprites 
for the foreground stuff (fast, but limited colours and sizes, unless you use 
some fancy tricks) or blits (slow, can use full colours, again can be optimised 
with some tricks).

If you choose to use the OS, so you can support all this nice hardware, you get 
a different set of problems. Do you stick with planar graphics or use chunky? 
Maybe do both, one for high end systems and one for low end. You wouldn't be 
able to use any hardware tricks, unless you made an AGA only version. And would 
you use CPU blitting (either direct into chipram, into fastmem [and copy to 
chip of gfx card memory]) or would you rely on graphics/cybergraphics libraries 
so you can use the hardware blitter of whatever display device is in use?

I'm not an expert, these are just general observations. And I'm sure there are 
people here who could tell you to ignore some of the options, because they're 
either overkill for this kind of project, or are just too damned awkward.


