Subject: @{b}Re: Assistance please...@{ub}

Hi Tony

> Can anyone help here.

I have this trouble all the time. I think the problem comes from the first 
statement where you are storing the string in your newtype. It seems as when 
you assign a string which is local (in this case Text$) to the string in your 
newtype, it allocates the string memory from the local variable space, which 
obviously gets lost (or should I say, can be overwritten) when you exit the 
function.

You can check this, inside the function when it stops, assign the string and 
then look at the newtype in the memory window to check the address. Run on to 
the second stop check the address in the memory window again. It should be the 
same, but now it just points to crap :(

I'm not sure of the best way around this, as I was able to simply use a single 
shared variable and left it at that. Obviously you're not able to do this.

Perhaps this is a bug in the Blitz string variable routines. You could try 
using a command which returns a string to see if you can get it to force it to 
allocate global memory. Something like:

*MCR\Headings\Column[0]\String = String$(Text$, 1)

Maybe?

