Hi,

Right, I found the bug, just need to wait till I get home so I can fix it 
(I don't have the latest source here). It might be a bit of a pain to fix 
this.



For those interested in the problem:

(Background)
With OS2, complex gadgets such as sliders, listviews, etc could be created 
which are actually made up of a number of single gadgets. OS2 
gadtools.library allocated different gadget ID's for each component of the 
complex gadgets, which is why you should start your ID's from a number such 
as 51 when coding for OS2+ in Blitz. Finding the correct part of a gadget 
was simple in the Blitz library, as only one gadget in the list (the actual 
master gadget I think) has the desired ID.

(Main part)
In OS3+, these complex gadgets now only use a single gadget ID for all 
their parts. While nice for normal programmers who can keep a pointer to 
the actual gadget created, doing this in a Blitz library would be difficult 
and probably quite pointless. It does mean now that when searching the 
gadget list you can find multiple gadgets (when using GTGadPtr) although, 
since the function can only return one value, we need to decide which 
pointer to return. The default behaviour in the Acid version of the library 
was to search for the last item in the list which had a matching ID and 
return a pointer to that. While this worked for some gadgets, the 
GTListviews and GTPalettes were broken. When I fixed this problem, I made 
it return the pointer to the first gadget with the matching ID. However, 
this then broke the prop gadgets which require you to return the pointer to 
the last gadget with a matching ID.


