OK, I got that, but you should have read the comments at the top ;) I don't 
speak German, but I managed to figure out that he got his idea from 
CXCommander (also on aminet, source in C and English) :)

Anyway, the important part is that both programs use private functions of 
commodities.library. Here's the important snippage:

/*** private functions of "commodities.library" ***/

#pragma libcall CxBase FindBroker 6c 801
#pragma libcall CxBase CopyBrokerList ba 801
#pragma libcall CxBase FreeBrokerList c0 801
#pragma libcall CxBase BrokerCommand c6 802

CxObj *FindBroker(char *);
LONG CopyBrokerList(struct List *);
LONG FreeBrokerList(struct List *);
LONG BrokerCommand(char *, LONG id);

The first number in the #pragma lines is the library offset. The second is 
the parameters. 802 is (a0,d0) in an FD file (parameters in that order) and 
801 is (a0). It's probably easiest to stick these private functions into 
your FD file for commodities.library and then fdconvert them.


