Hi amorel

> I`m sure there is a trick to have dual playfields working with more than 16
> colours per bitmap. But how? What about more than 2? 

Not using the hardware as it is. Maybe if you wrote your own insane-o huge 
copperlist or something, but the dual playfields are limited to 16 colours 
because AGA displays can only handle 8 bitplanes. So when you go to 2 
playfields, it gives half the bitplanes to each playfield, resulting in 4 
playfields each and therefore 16 colours. I'm not sure how well poking around 
in the copperlist changing colours would work either.

You can change the distribution of the playfields. For example playfield 1 has 
32 colours (5 bitplanes) and playfield 2 has 8 colours (3 bitplanes), and so on.

As for more than 2 playfields, you could use hardware sprites. You can put 
sprites in between playefields and in fornt and behind them, so you could end 
up with a display with 5 playfields. I think you could even stick more sprites 
in between them too. But then you'd need something like multiplexed or 
tesselated (that the right word? Sami and Teemu [hope I got the name right] 
were speaking about this a while ago) sprites, to fill the full width of the 
display.

I'm sure a demo coder would be able to tell you properly if you know one :)


