> 
> Another idea might be to have an index in the beginning of each file
> that has the offset in bytes where each letter is located and then
> you automagically know how long the word is by using the next offset
> and can jump to it very fast.

Anther idea is to break the word up into a chain of pointers
corresponding to the letters in the word and end the chain with a
null. If you hit a null before you run out of letters in the word or
don't have a pointer corresponding to the next letter, you know it's
not in the dictionary. The advantage is that the same chain could
correspond to several words with the same initial letters. Adding
another word would just mean adding extra pointers for the final few
letters.

It would be quick access, more compact and would not involve sorting
the dictionary to add more words.

